From: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Date: 2026-05-13
Subject: [PATCH] ps4_mts: v107 — skip_probe module param for BAR0 snapshot mode

After 14 patches (v82..v105) all 5 latch-trigger hypotheses for BAR+0x04
bit 0 have been falsified live.  Kimi v107 final verdict: latch is
write-once per power cycle, armed by a boot-time-only condition that
software cannot reproduce.

The only remaining experiment that can distinguish "missed register"
from "silicon-level interlock" is to capture the BAR0 state when the
hardware is in a known-working state (Orbis-initialized) and diff
against our v97 broken-TX state.

This patch adds a kernel cmdline parameter `ps4_mts.skip_probe=1` that
makes mts_probe return -ENODEV BEFORE any hardware register is touched.
With this flag set:

  - PCI subsystem still enumerates 00:14.1
  - BAR0 sysfs node /sys/bus/pci/devices/0000:00:14.1/resource0 remains
    mmap-able from userspace
  - Our driver does NOT call mts_parent_prelude() (which would reset
    the switch chip and destroy the bootloader/Orbis state)
  - Our driver does NOT call mts_mac_init() (which would re-arm latch
    in our broken way)

Usage (for snapshot mode):

  bootargs: ... ps4_mts.skip_probe=1 ...

Then in Linux userspace:

  python3 -c '
  import mmap, os
  fd = os.open("/sys/bus/pci/devices/0000:00:14.1/resource0", os.O_RDWR)
  m = mmap.mmap(fd, 4096)
  with open("/tmp/orbis-mts-bar0.bin", "wb") as f:
      f.write(m[:4096])
  '

Then compare:

  xxd orbis-mts-bar0.bin > orbis.txt
  xxd v97-mts-bar0.bin   > linux.txt
  diff orbis.txt linux.txt

Any line that differs (other than the known status-bit outputs at
0x004/0x06c) is a candidate missing register.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
---
 drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c | 19 +++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 19 insertions(+)

--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -1799,12 +1799,31 @@

 /* end of v93 netdev block */

+/*
+ * v107: when set to 1 via bootargs (ps4_mts.skip_probe=1), mts_probe returns
+ * -ENODEV before touching ANY hardware register.  PCI enumeration still
+ * happens, BAR0 is still assigned, and /sys/bus/pci/devices/0000:00:14.1/
+ * resource0 remains mmap-able from userspace.  Used to capture a BAR0
+ * snapshot of the hardware in Orbis-initialized state for diff analysis
+ * against our v97 broken-TX state.
+ */
+static int skip_probe;
+module_param(skip_probe, int, 0444);
+MODULE_PARM_DESC(skip_probe,
+		 "If 1, skip probe-time hardware init (BAR0 snapshot mode).");
+
 static int mts_probe(struct pci_dev *pdev, const struct pci_device_id *id)
 {
 	struct net_device *ndev;
 	struct mts *mts;
 	int ret, i;

+	if (skip_probe) {
+		dev_info(&pdev->dev,
+			 "ps4_mts: skip_probe=1, NOT touching hardware (BAR0 snapshot mode)\n");
+		return -ENODEV;
+	}
+
 	/* v93: alloc_etherdev_mqs(priv_size, txqs, rxqs) — allocates net_device
 	 * + private (struct mts) in one go.  Single TX queue, single RX queue.
 	 * Auto-freed by devm. */
